article-header container "><div class="article-header__inner"><div class="article-header__inner__category t_tag t_tag--header" itemprop="articleSection"><a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/behavior/">Behavior</a></div><h1 class="article-header__title t_article-title" itemprop="headline">How Did the "Smile" Become a Friendly Gesture in Humans?</h1><p class="t_article-subtitle">In almost all other species, especially primates, baring one's teeth is a threat or a show of potential force.&nbsp;Are there any cultures in which smiling is not considered friendly?</p><div class="article-header__divider"><ul role="presentation" class="meta-list t_meta"><li class="meta-list__item"><time itemprop="datePublished" content="October 21, 1999">October 21, 1999</time></li></ul></div></div></header><div class="article-progress" data-behavior="article_progress"><div class="article-progress__bar"></div><div class="article-grid-outer container "><div class="article-grid"><aside class="article-grid__share"><div class="share-box tooltip-outer"><ul class="share-box__inner"><li class="share-box__inner__item"><a href="#" data-sharer-url="http://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-did-the-smile-become-a-friendly-gesture-in-humans/" class="share-box__inner__item__link" data-social-provider="Facebook" data-behavior="sharer" data-tooltip-hover data-tooltip-top data-tooltip-width="225" data-tooltip-id="facebook-tooltip" data-track="click"data-track-label="facebook_icon"data-track-category="share_icon"data-track-action="link"><span class="icon icon__facebook--black"></span></a><div class="tooltip__label">Share on Facebook</div></li><li class="share-box__inner__item"><a href="#" class="share-box__inner__item__link" data-social-provider="Twitter" data-behavior="sharer" data-sharer-url="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-did-the-smile-become-a-friendly-gesture-in-humans/&amp;text=How Did the &quot